title: For Sale/Trade:  Original 1917 WWI German Geweh Saw Back M1898/05, Sawback Bayonet w/scabbard
postcontent:
ORIGINAL, untouched, unsharpened, unpolished antique WW1 German Geweh 98 Saw Back M1898/05 bayonet.  Truly a rare find in this condition.  Would make a perfect addition for a WW1 Gew or WW1 bayonet collection.  Highly sought after and collectable due to it being a saw back bayonet version of the classic M1898/05 second pattern design - AND the saw blade scallops appear to slightly worn down due to authentic use!  This is an Emperial German WW1 era1917 production bayonet based upon the number 17 stamped below the Royal Cypher of Kaiser Emporer "W"ilhiem crest on the side of the bayonet as depicted in the pictures.  This is a unique un-tampered saw back bayonet (made famous by the book titled "All is Quiet on the Western Front").  This German saw back bayonet design has a rich history - while useful for cutting brush and debris, it inflicted horrific damage when used in combat.  It was so hated that Germans captured with this bayonet attached on their rifles were executed.  German officers quickly passed an order that all sawback bayonets be ground down to have smooth edges on both sides.  This one survived.  $325 obo  Many more pictures available upon request.

I can be contacted via email or phone/text: REDACTED

Here is a little more info; found on the Internet---
The 1871 Army pistol (sometimes referred to as the Army and Navy Model). This was the final redesign. The trigger and trigger guard were moved forward on the receiver, and a spur was added to the receiver behind the hammer to allow for a better grip. A firing pin retractor was added, and a rotating extractor was designed. The front sight was changed from a bead to a blade, and the lock-work was also redesigned.  The gun was available in .50 center-fire, but could be special ordered in .22 rimfire. It was designed for the U.S. military, but was never actually sold to them. Approximately 6,000 were made.

postcontent: Colt AR-15 A2 Government model.  This model is often referred to as the "transition model" because it was produced and released for public sale right at the time of the original gun ban. Colt elected to release the inventory they had, but not before they ground off the bayonet lug. There were very few of these models released before colt ceased production and release of the government model to the general public altogether and went to the "Sporter" version. These rifles are one of a kind run. They have all the M-16/A2 features less the bayonet lug. Only a few hundred were produced in a run marked "AR – 15 A2 government model" These rifles have no sear blocks or other ban modifications and the barrels are the USGIM16A2 1:7 chrome lined MP tested threaded barrels. The rifle also has the A-2 flash hider. These models are rare and recognized in all your Firearms reference guides. title: For Sale:  VZ-58/2008, never fired
postcontent:
I have a VZ-58/2008 I got a while back new and haven't had time to take it out to shoot yet.  I'd like to keep it but looking for work right now and need to fix my truck before it breaks down on me.

If you know anything about cold war guns, these are hard to find.  Although the look similar to an AK-47 and shoots the same rounds, it is definitely NOT an AK.    It is arguably more reliable and more accurate than an AK or SKS.

Some of the differences are:

Milled receiver, not stamped like AKs and SKSs.
-Slightly smaller and lighter than an AK, 7lbs with an empty mag.  35" long with stock unfolded, 26" folded (Without bayonet attached)
-Striker fired
-Bolt stays open in when the last round is fired.
-Fewer parts, more reliable bolt assembly
-Easier safety to operate, can be switched on or off with the trigger finger while still holding the gun, the AK safety leaves an opening where debris can get in.
-More accurate and reliable than AKs and SKSs
-Bayonet is quickly attached or detached and can be used as a stand alone knife.
-Open bolt design makes stovepipes extremely unlikely.   When looking into this gun, I could not find an incident of one.

I'm not thrilled when I have to sell one of my guns so no low ballers please!  I will include 3 magazines, Bayonet with sheath and shoulder strap. 

Thanks for reading, you can reach me at FOUR FIVE SIX 9654.  Local OKC 40 FIVE area code.

title: For Sale:  Complete PSA 6.8 SPCII Upper 20" barrel + BCG + ammo + mags + brass
postcontent:
For sale is a like-new complete Palmetto State Armory upper receiver assembly chambered in 6.8 SPCII. 1/11 twist, 20" heavy profile barrel, magnetic particle inspected chrome-lined bore and chamber. Check the link at the bottom of the page for the manufacturer's specs. Includes a 6.8 bolt carrier group, mags, and ammo, everything you need to start shooting 6.8 today with your standard AR lower receiver. I've fired this upper at the range using three different brands of lower receivers without any problems whatsoever. I paid $500 for the upper assembly in December, and I've invested another $450 in upgraded parts and gunsmith fees. Willing to ship in the original PSA box, buyer pays shipping costs. 

This upper assembly was purchased new from PSA in December 2013 and has fired a grand total of 80 rounds of 110g Hornady varmint express V-MAX. I collected the brass and will include the 80 empty once-fired cases if you are a reloader. I'll also throw in four 20-round boxes of Hornady varmint express 6.8 if you meet my asking price. When you can find it, this ammo sells locally for about $25 a box. I'll also include a Precision Reflex Industries 5-round 6.8 magazine (which functions flawlessly and can fit up to 9 rounds) and two C-Products Defense 10-round 6.8 magazines (which I have not had great luck with).  

I had the gunsmiths at Wiser Owl Firearms & Tactical in Miramar install a Parallax Tactical 15" free-float super slim rail and a Midwest Industries low-profile gas block in December 2013. The rail is a $200 upgrade, the low-pro gas block another $50. This sale also includes an assembled Maxim Firearms 6.8 SPC bolt carrier group, which retails for $150. I don't know much about the Maxim BCG, but it was the only 6.8 BCG I could find for sale, anywhere, when I bought the upper. 

I'm asking $750, cash, meet at a neutral location in San Diego county. I'd prefer to meet at a gun store, but would be willing to go elsewhere if necessary. I'll consider trade offers. I'll accept PayPal to ship it, or suggest another payment method. I've got more than $900 invested in this upper, not including the $100 in magazines and $100+ in ammo that is included in the sale. Please no lowball offers.

The link to the original upper assembly on the PSA website is below.

Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun is the new product from Turkish company Akdal Arms. This weapon is intended for civilian and security use, and mimics the famous M16 rifle in its layout and placement of most controls. It is remarkably light for its caliber and size, because of extensive use of modern, high strength plastics.

Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun utilizes conventional gas-operated action with annual (ring-type) gas piston, which is located around the support tube that runs below the barrel. Return spring is also located around the same tube, which is concealed by enlarged polymer handguards. Barrel is quick-removable from upper receiver, barrel locking is achieved by tilting locking piece inside the bolt, which engages the barrel extension. Charging handle is attached to the bolt and projects on the right side of the receiver. The upper receiver is manufactured from aluminum alloy; lower receiver, along with pistol grip and shoulder stock, is manufactured as one piece from impact-resistant polymer. Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun utilizes detachable box magazines, each holding 5 rounds; an M16-style bolt stop and bolt release button are incorporated into the lower receiver. Manual safety also duplicates M16-style, being located on the left side of the receiver, above the pistol grip. Standard sights include front post, installed on the M16-style removable base, and a detachable M16A2-style carrying handle with built-in diopter sight.

Taurus family of semi-auto pistols all feature the Taurus Security System, which provides instant-ready defense with built-in ability to secure your pistol and make it inoperable at the turn of a key. When the Security System is engaged, the pistol cannot be fired or cocked and the gun's manual safety cannot be disengaged. As with our revolver Security System, the device is part of the firearm and cannot be lost, and the same special Security Key works for both the revolver and pistol Systems (two keys come with each gun). To engage: simply insert the Key into the button on the rear or side of the pistol and rotate one-quarter turn clockwise. This engages the Security System. This releases the Security System, yet leaves the pistol's manual safety in the "safe" position until you are ready to release it yourself and fire the gun. 

Transfer Bar
